2. `q = ∞`: Similarly, `‖f * g‖_∞ ≤ ‖f‖_∞ * ‖g‖_∞`. This is also trivial.
3. `r = ∞`: We need `‖f * g‖_∞ ≤ ‖f‖_p * ‖g‖_q`. But `‖f * g‖_∞ = ‖f‖_∞ * ‖g‖_∞`. Since `p, q` are finite (as they are not `∞` in this case), `‖f‖_p ≤ ‖f‖_∞` and `‖g‖_q ≤ ‖g‖_∞`. So `‖f‖_p * ‖g‖_q ≤ ‖f‖_∞ * ‖g‖_∞ = ‖f * g‖_∞`. This requires more detailed work.
4. `p = ∞`: We need `‖f * g‖_r ≤ ‖f‖_∞ * ‖g‖_q`. Since `r` is finite, `‖f * g‖_r ≤ ‖f * g‖_∞ = ‖f‖_∞ * ‖g‖_∞`. And `‖f‖_∞ * ‖g‖_q ≤ ‖f‖_∞ * ‖g‖_∞ = ‖f * g‖_∞`. This requires more detailed work.
5. `q = ∞`: We need `‖f * g‖_r ≤ ‖f‖_p * ‖g‖_∞`. Similar to the previous case.
6. `r = ∞`: We need `‖f * g‖_∞ ≤ ‖f‖_p * ‖g‖_q`. This is the case where `1/p + 1/q = 1`. This is the standard Holder inequality.

